    The underlying issue is that the mathematics of the diagonal in a typed setting is more delicate than Guard's
     one-level natural-number story suggests. Guard can write sub(j,j) once and read it at either level; we
    cannot. Until the agent has internalised (a) which functor realises Guard's sub in our setting (answer: sub,
    not subT, because of cor), and (b) that the code-level diagonal identity is a named lemma proved by induction
     on F, not a definitional equality, the file will not come out fast.

    The fix is not to grind harder. It is to stop, state the two meta lemmas explicitly (codeCommutes by
    induction on Formula; the diagonal identity as its specialisation at F), use sub instead of subT, and then
    write Thm 11 in a dozen lines that compose them. If the agent is not doing that structural work first, it is
    looping on surface syntax.

